results.notes:
Partially immersed to raised black perithecia on hymenial surface of Xanthoria elegans apothecia. Host thallus is located on sheltered sandstone substrate, facing northwest direction out of direct sunlight, in Juniperus osteosperma-Artemisia woodland.

Perithecia wall is dark brown-black with long branched paraphyses; additionally, the bottom of each perithecium is also darkly pigmented. Spores are hyaline, ellipsoid, and commonly 1-septate with one or two locules within each cell.

Identification of Zwackhiomyces coepulonus is based on characteristics of spore and ascomata morphology, in addition to the host.

Ref: ascofrance.com & lichenportal.org
